The '''2009 flu pandemic in the United States''' was a [[pandemic]] experienced in the [[United States]] of a novel strain of the [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1#2009 Influenza A.28H1N1.29 pandemic|Influenza A/H1N1]] virus, commonly referred to as '[[swine flu]]', that began in the spring of 2009. The virus had spread to the US from an [[2009 swine flu outbreak in Mexico|outbreak in Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Outbreak of Swine-Origin Influenza A (H1n1) Virus Infection|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm58d0430a2.htm|publisher=CDC|date=April 30, 2009|accessdate=June 11, 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090606130423/http://www.cdc.gov/MMWR/preview/mmwrhtml/mm58d0430a2.htm| archivedate= 6 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

As of mid-March 2010, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) estimated that about 59 million Americans contracted the H1N1 virus, 265,000 were hospitalized as a result, and 12,000 died.<ref>{{cite news| title=Swine flu danger appears to be ebbing |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/19/science/la-sci-swine-flu20-2010mar20 |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=March 19, 2010| author= Thomas H. Maugh II| accessdate= March 20, 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100323061750/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/19/science/la-sci-swine-flu20-2010mar20| archivedate= 23 March 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==History==
The earliest reported cases in the US began appearing in late March 2009, in California,<ref name="mmwr5815a5">
{{cite journal
|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5815a5.htm
|title=Swine Influenza A (H1N1) Infection in Two Children --- Southern California, March--April 2009
|date=2009-04-24
|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control]]
|work=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]]
|volume=58 (Dispatch)
|issue=15
|pages=400–402
|accessdate=2009-10-04
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091001131355/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5815a5.htm| archivedate= 1 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name="cdcfirst">{{cite web| title=CDC Press Briefing Transcripts April 23, 2009|url=http://www.cdc.gov/media/transcripts/2009/t090423.htm|publisher=CDC|accessdate=June 11, 2009|date=April 23, 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090605145129/http://www.cdc.gov/media/transcripts/2009/t090423.htm| archivedate= 5 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> then spread to infect people in Texas, New York, and assorted other states by mid-April. This spread continued across the country's population and by the end of May had infected citizens in all 50 states.  The pattern continued through June of the same year.  The total number of confirmed cases varied from 27,717<ref name="CDC-Confirmed">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/|title=H1N1 Flu (Swine Flu)|work=H1N1 Flu|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|date=2009-05-06 (11:00 EDT)|accessdate=2009-05-06|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jhOamgHk|archivedate=2009-09-10|deadurl=no}}</ref> ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) confirmed and probable cases) and 25,453<ref name="Wiki-Template">{{cite web|title=Template:2009 US swine flu otbreak table|accessdate=June 11, 2009|url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:2009_US_swine_flu_outbreak_table|publisher=Wikipedia| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090613030045/http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:2009_US_swine_flu_outbreak_table| archivedate= 13 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> (total of all state confirmed cases) as of June 26, 2009.

Towards the middle of June 2009, the number of US cases surpassed those of Mexico, which had been the previous leader in diagnosed cases of the disease. Toward the end of June 2009, the number of deaths related to the virus in the US surpassed those of all other countries as well.

On June 25, the CDC released information revealing that there were more than likely over one million (1,000,000) cases of the disease in the US, most of which had not been reported or diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|title=1 Million Americans Likely Stricken by Swine Flu: CDC|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 25, 2009|date=June 25, 2009|url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/hscout/2009/06/25/hscout628467.html| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090627123015/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/hscout/2009/06/25/hscout628467.html| archivedate= 27 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US Swine Flu Cases May Have Hit 1 Million|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=June 25, 2009|date=June 25, 2009|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hjdCHrP82YTFser5vD6CzTK1az6wD991UK9O1}}</ref>

Deaths relating to this new strain of influenza began appearing in the US in late April, and by early June 15, states had reported fatalities related to or directly occurring from the virus.  These deaths totaled at 4,000 as of November 15, 2009.<ref name="Wiki-Template" />

The CDC is distributing [[2009 flu pandemic vaccine|vaccine]] for the novel flu strain<ref>http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/vaccination/vaccinesupply.htm</ref> using mechanisms already in place for its Vaccines for Children (VFC) program.<ref>http://www.cdc.gov/H1N1flu/vaccination/statelocal/centralized_distribution_qa.htm</ref>

On October 24, 2009, President [[Barack Obama]] declared Swine Flu a national emergency in the United States.

On November 12, 2009, the CDC reported an estimated 22 million Americans had been infected with 2009 A H1N1 and 4,000 Americans have died.<ref>http://www.cdc.gov/media/transcripts/2009/t091112.htm</ref>

On December 10, 2009, the CDC reported an estimated 50 million Americans or 1-6 people had been infected with the 2009 A H1N1 Virus and 10,000 American have died, by which time the vaccine was beginning to be widely distributed to the general public by several states.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5AO3Z420091210 | work=Reuters | title=Swine flu has killed 10,000 Americans since April | date=2009-12-10| accessdate= 13 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091217193529/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5AO3Z420091210?| archivedate= 17 December 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref>

On December 23, 2009 the CDC reported the Reduction of The Disease by 59% percent and only 3 states reporting widespread
and the disease is expected to end in The United States in January 2010.

On January 15, 2010, the CDC released new estimate figures for swine flu, saying it has sickened about 55 million Americans and killed about 11,160 from April through mid-December.<ref>http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/34880176/ns/health-cold_and_flu</ref>

On February 12, 2010, the CDC released updated estimate figures for swine flu, reporting that, in total, 57 million Americans had been sickened, 257,000 had been hospitalised and 11,690 people had died (including 1,180 children) due to swine flu from April through to mid-January.<ref>http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/35367744/ns/health-cold_and_flu/</ref>

==Initial cases==
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) identified the first two A/09(H1N1) swine flu cases in California on April 17, 2009, via the Border Infectious Disease Program,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2009/may/07/border-disease-program-helped-sound-alarm-swine-fl/ |title=Border Disease Program Helped Sound Alarm on Swine Flu |accessdate=2010-09-02 |last= |first= |coauthors= |date= |format= |work= |publisher=KPBS San Diego |pages= |quote= }}</ref> for the San Diego County child, and a naval research facility studying a special diagnostic test, where influenza sample from the child from Imperial County was tested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/media/transcripts/2009/t090423.htm|title=CDC Briefing on Public Health Investigation of Human Cases of Swine Influenza|publisher=CDC|date=2009-04-23|accessdate=April 26, 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090426093348/http://www.cdc.gov/media/transcripts/2009/t090423.htm| archivedate= 26 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> By April 21, enhanced surveillance was established to search for additional cases in both California and Texas and the CDC determined that the virus strain was genetically similar to the previously known A(H1N1) swine flu circulating among pigs in the United States since about 1999.

It was established that the virus was a combination of human, North American swine, and Eurasian swine influenza viruses; the viruses from the initial two Californian cases were also noted to be resistant to [[amantadine]] and [[rimantadine]], two common influenza antiviral drugs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmWR/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5815a5.htm|title=Swine Influenza A (H1N1) Infection in Two Children --- Southern California, March--April 2009|publisher=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]]|author=CDC|date=April 21, 2009|accessdate=April 26, 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090426212017/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5815a5.htm| archivedate= 26 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> No contact with pigs was found for any of the seven Californian nor either of the two Texas cases, suggesting human-to-human transmission of the virus.

On April 28, 2009, the director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] confirmed the first official US death of swine flu. Tests confirmed that a 23-month old toddler from Mexico, who was probably infected there, died on April 27 from the flu while visiting Texas.<ref name="fatality1">{{cite news | url = http://cnnwire.blogs.cnn.com/2009/04/29/swine-flu-fatality-in-texas-likely-infected-in-mexico-official-says/ | work=CNN | title=Swine flu fatality in Texas likely infected in Mexico, official says| accessdate= 24 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

==Outbreak across the US==
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
[[Image:WhoLab18.GIF|thumb|left|260px|CDC report for the 2008-2009 flu season week 18 (May 17), subtypes and percent positive tests]]
Cases of H1N1 spread rapidly across the United States, with particularly severe outbreaks in Texas, New York, Utah, and California. Early cases were associated with recent travel to Mexico; many were students who had traveled to Mexico for Spring Break.<ref name = CBS090504>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/05/04/health/main4988673.shtml |title=Queens School At Flu Epicenter Reopens |publisher=CBS News |date= May 4, 2009|accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090507080303/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/05/04/health/main4988673.shtml| archivedate= 7 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On May 4, 2009, the CDC reported one death, 286 confirmed cases of H1N1 flu across 36 states, 35 hospitalizations, and expects H1N1 to eventually spread to all states. A large number of cases, according to medics, have happened in the days that preceded the launch of the alert and came out only in these days due to a massive backlog.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUKTRE5435R220090504|title=Flu spreads across U.S., officials weigh measures &#124; Top News &#124; Reuters|publisher=Uk.reuters.com|date=2009-02-09|accessdate=2009-05-05| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090507072145/http://uk.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUKTRE5435R220090504| archivedate= 7 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>  By May 5, 2009, the number had risen to 403<ref name="http1">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/|title=CDC H1N1 Flu|publisher=Cdc.gov|date=|accessdate=2009-05-06|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jhOamgHk|archivedate=2009-09-10|deadurl=no}}</ref> and a second death was reported in Texas.<ref name="hostednews1">{{cite web|author=Christopher Sherman|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hNkUqwzLRY-8nSc_6e5AM0Vf2FIgD9809L7G0|title=The Associated Press: Texas confirms first flu death of US resident|publisher=Google.com|date=|accessdate=2009-05-05}}</ref> The CDC and government officials had expressed cautious optimism about the severity and spread of H1N1.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/05/health/05flu.html?_r=1&ref=americas | work=The New York Times | title=Health Officials Begin to Ease Public Alerts About Swine Flu | first1=Gardiner | last1=Harris | first2=Elisabeth | last2=Malkin | date=2009-05-05| accessdate= 24 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090516090649/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/05/health/05flu.html?_r=1&ref=americas| archivedate= 16 May 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bowman|first=Michael|url=http://www.voanews.com/english/2009-05-04-voa59.cfm|title=US Officials 'Cautiously Optimistic' About Swine Flu Spread|publisher=VOA News|date=2008-07-15|accessdate=2009-05-05| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090506013102/http://www.voanews.com/english/2009-05-04-voa59.cfm| archivedate= 6 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

Changes in surveillance of cases of [[influenza-like illness]], including new guidelines for identifying cases to test, increased laboratory testing, and new test kits able to distinguish this novel strain, resulted in a spike in the percent of cases tested positive for influenza.  Of the positive cases, about a third were due to the novel strain.  Also found were a substantial number of cases where the strain could not be subtyped.<ref name=CDC090515>{{cite journal
 |title=2008-2009 Influenza Season Week 18 ending May 9, 2009
 |journal=FluView: A Weekly Influenza Surveillance Report Prepared by the Influenza Division
 |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]
 |date=2009-05-15
 |url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/
 |accessdate=2009-05-17
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090517044139/http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/| archivedate= 17 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

[[File:Bigpi43(2009).GIF|thumb|260px|Pneumonia and influenza deaths in 122 US cities, 5 years through October 2009]]
The proportion of US deaths due to pneumonia and influenza climbed above the epidemic threshold in the 2007–2008 winter flu season but not in the 2008–2009 season.  Although the 2009 H1N1 outbreak reached epidemic levels of infection early in 2009, it did not contribute to epidemic levels of pneumonia and influenza related deaths until October 2009.

