===Other federal agencies===
;Department of Homeland Security
Secretary Napolitano stated that DHS is the principal federal office for incidents such as the current H1N1 flu outbreak, and “Under that role, we have been leading a true collaborative effort.”<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhs.gov/ynews/testimony/testimony_1241017177339.shtm|title=DHS: Testimony by Secretary Napolitano to the Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs on Federal Coordination in Response to the H1N1 Flu Outbreak|publisher=Dhs.gov|date=2009-04-29|accessdate=2009-05-05| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090506165457/http://www.dhs.gov/ynews/testimony/testimony_1241017177339.shtm| archivedate= 6 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The Department of Homeland Security has a document, dated November 1, 2005, entitled "National Strategy for Pandemic Influenza", detailing planning for potential pandemics. http://www.pandemicflu.gov/plan/federal/pandemic-influenza.pdf
;State Department
The State Department suggested travelers to Mexico stay alert and comply with guidance from Mexican public health officials, but did not impose any travel restrictions on US citizens to Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mexico.usembassy.gov/eng/eacs_warden_090425update_FluOutbreak.html |title=Threats of Increased Violence in Ciudad Juarez during the weekend of May 23–25, 2008 |publisher=Mexico.usembassy.gov |date= |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090510052220/http://mexico.usembassy.gov/eng/eacs_warden_090425update_FluOutbreak.html| archivedate= 10 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> However, the State Department did recommend US citizens avoid non-essential travel to Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/pa/pa_3028.html |title=Travel Alert – 2009-H1N1 Influenza |publisher=Travel.state.gov |date= |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090506214913/http://www.travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/pa/pa_3028.html| archivedate= 6 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
;Department of Agriculture
The Department of Agriculture (USDA) reported no swine in the US have been infected so far, but the USDA is monitoring swine across the US for signs of infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usda.gov/wps/portal/?contentidonly=true&contentid=2009/04/0131.xml |title=Release No. 0131.09 |publisher=Usda.gov |date= |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090506220131/http://www.usda.gov/wps/portal/?contentidonly=true&contentid=2009/04/0131.xml| archivedate= 6 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
;Department of Commerce
The Department of Commerce sent a letter to Russia and China requesting that those countries lift their ban on American pork products.<ref>{{cite web|author=ksullivan |url=http://www.commerce.gov/NewsRoom/PressReleases_FactSheets/PROD01_007941 |title=Department of Commerce – Press Releases, Fact Sheets and Opinion Editorials – Commerce Secretary Gary Locke Urges China, Russia to End Ban on U.S. Pork |publisher=Commerce.gov |date=2009-05-01 |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090507034844/http://www.commerce.gov/NewsRoom/PressReleases_FactSheets/PROD01_007941| archivedate= 7 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
;Department of Defense
The Department of Defense (DOD) is monitoring the swine flu situation and has contingency plans to deal with such outbreaks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=54088 |title=DefenseLink News Article: Military Monitors H1N1 Flu With Focus on Protecting Force |publisher=Defenselink.mil |date= |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090506080713/http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=54088| archivedate= 6 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> As of May 7, 2009, the DOD reports 104 confirmed cases among Armed Forces personnel and their families. DOD maintains a daily summary and map.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fhp.osd.mil/aiWatchboard/ |title=DoD Pandemic Influenza Watchboard – U.S. DoD Official Website |publisher=Fhp.osd.mil |date= |accessdate=2009-05-19| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090525185145/http://fhp.osd.mil/aiWatchboard/| archivedate= 25 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
;Department of Education
The Department of Education is providing guidance to schools in the US affected by swine flu, as well as precautions to take.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edgovblogs.org/duncan/2009/04/additional-flu-resources-for-school-leaders-seeking-guidance/ |title=Additional Flu Resources for School Leaders Seeking Guidance – ED.gov Blog |publisher=Edgovblogs.org |date=2009-04-29 |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090505072306/http://www.edgovblogs.org/duncan/2009/04/additional-flu-resources-for-school-leaders-seeking-guidance/| archivedate= 5 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===State and local===
Schools closed in many states in response to local flu outbreaks. By April 30, 2009, 300 U.S. schools and school districts had announced closures in response to the outbreak, giving 169,000 students time off.<ref name="schools">{{cite news|title=US closes 300 schools amid swine flu scare|date=April 30, 2009|agency=AFP|accessdate=April 30, 2009|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iVi40liSCcy6QuawOiik3az8ceiA}}</ref> On May 4, 2009, about 533 schools in 24 states in the U.S. were closed, affecting about 330,000 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=aGmubXeIXSqI&refer=asia|title=Swine Flu Sickens 1, 490 as Answers Sought in South (Update4)|publisher=Bloomberg.com|date=2005-05-30|accessdate=2009-05-05}}</ref> On September 25, 2009, forty-two schools were closed in eight states as the second wave of the pandemic began.<ref>{{cite news|title=Swine Flu Surge Closes Schools, Tests Hospitals - washingtonpost.com <!-- BOT GENERATED TITLE -->|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/09/26/AR2009092601254.html?hpid=topnews|work=The Washington Post|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kAv3Gqrr|archivedate=2009-09-30|deadurl=no|accessdate=2009-09-28 | first=Rob | last=Stein | date=2009-09-27}}</ref>

On May 5, [[Kathleen Sebelius]] stated in a CDC news conference that school closures for single confirmed cases of H1N1 influenza were unnecessary, but that parents keep their child home if he or she displays an influenza-like illness.<!-- transcript & mp3 will be released soon; this is from the audio webcast --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/press/|title=CDC Press Briefing Transcripts May 5, 2009|date=2009-05-05|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control]]|accessdate=2009-05-05| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090504031751/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/press/| archivedate= 4 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===Travel industry===
